  "prompt": "How does the law define illegal money laundering activities?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Key elements typically include:\n\n1. Three primary stages:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (concealing source through complex transactions)\n- Integration (withdrawing transformed money as seemingly legitimate)\n\n2. Specific illegal activities often include:\n- Disguising origins of criminal proceeds\n- Transferring money through multiple accounts\n- Structuring transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n- Using shell companies or offshore accounts\n\n3. Legal definitions vary by jurisdiction, but most countries criminalize:\n- Knowingly concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n- Attempting to make illegal funds appear legitimate\n- Facilitating financial transactions to hide criminal origins\n\n4. Typical predicate crimes generating laundered funds:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Illegal gambling\n- Theft\n- Terrorist financing\n\n5. Regulatory frameworks like Bank Secrecy Act in US and similar international laws require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions.\n\nThe precise legal definition can vary between different legal systems, so consulting specific jurisdictional statutes is recommended for definitive details.",
